## Theorem: translated_imo_2018_p1

Theorem: translated_imo_2018_p1
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: d = on_line d a b
Given: e = on_line e a c, on_circle e a d
Given: f = on_bline f b d, on_circle f o a
Given: g = on_bline g e c, on_circle g o a
Prove: prove that line de ∥ line fg

Goal: para d e f g

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The points f and g are chosen as the second intersections of the circumcircle of ABC with the perpendicular bisectors of BD and CE, so their positions are determined by equal-power and equal-distance relations that let us compare the directions of DE and FG via a standard angle/chord computation.",
  "plan": [
    "Use the cyclicity of A,B,C,F,G to express angles involving F and G.",
    "Translate the perpendicular-bisector conditions into equal distances, then into power-of-a-point relations on the circumcircle.",
    "Compute the relevant ratios or angles along lines through D,E with the circle.",
    "Show that the angle between DE and FG is zero, hence the lines are parallel."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "Points A, B, C, F, and G lie on the same circle, namely the circle with center O through A, B, C.",
      "reasoning": "By definition, O is the circumcenter of triangle ABC, so circle O passes through A, B, and C. The conditions on F and G say that F and G lie on circle O through A, hence F and G also lie on this same circle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circumcenter/circle through three points"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Since F lies on the perpendicular bisector of BD, we have FB = FD; since G lies on the perpendicular bisector of CE, we have GC = GE.",
      "reasoning": "A point on the perpendicular bisector of a segment is equidistant from the endpoints of that segment. Applying this to the given perpendicular-bisector conditions gives the stated equalities.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicular bisector"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The equalities FB = FD and GC = GE determine F and G as the second intersections of the circumcircle (ABC) with circles centered at B and C of radii BD and CE, respectively.",
      "reasoning": "Because F and G are also on the circumcircle through A,B,C, each point is characterized as lying on two circles: the circumcircle and the circle forced by the perpendicular-bisector equality. This reformulation will allow chord/angle comparisons on the circumcircle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "step 2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The angle between line DF and line AB equals the angle between line DE and line AC, and the corresponding angle between line FG and line DE is controlled by the same circular chord data.",
      "reasoning": "Since D lies on AB and E lies on AC, any angle involving D or E with AB or AC can be rewritten in terms of the triangles formed with the cyclic points A,B,C,F,G. The key consequence is that the directions of DF and EG are encoded by equal-chord relations on the common circumcircle.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "step 2",
        "inscribed angle theorem"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The directed angle from line DE to line FG is zero.",
      "reasoning": "Using the cyclic configuration and the equal-distance conditions FB = FD and GC = GE, one obtains the same angle relation for the segment through D to F as for the segment through E to G, so the two lines have the same direction. Therefore DE and FG are parallel.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "step 2",
        "inscribed angle theorem",
        "congruence from equal chords"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "line DE ∥ line FG.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the conclusion of the previous step.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 5"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "line de ∥ line fg"
}

